    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Recycling Is Effective</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dave Newman letter argues that recycling is clearly more environmentally friendly and as cost-effective as landfills (Aug 8 John Tierney column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Negatives of Recycling in New York,'' by John Tierney (Big City column, Aug. 8): While it is true that recycling is not financially self-supporting, it is neither more nor less expensive than the landfilling process.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Negatives of Recycling in New York,'' by John Tierney (Big City column, Aug. 8): While it is true that recycling is not financially self-supporting, it is neither more nor less expensive than the landfilling process.</p>
        <p>Curbside collection of recyclables may be more environmentally damaging than collection of an equivalent amount of garbage, but only if one ignores the clear trend toward shortfall in landfill capacity, as well as the environmental degradation and health hazards that are associated with landfills.</p>
        <p>When the energy savings attained from manufacturing with recycled materials and related reductions in pollution (and pollution abatement costs) are factored in, recycling is clearly more environmentally friendly and cost-effective. Recycling and source reduction are effective methods of conserving energy, cutting pollution and conserving natural resources.</p>
        <p>DAVE NEWMAN  Brooklyn, Aug. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
